Certainly! Below is a simple example of a web app contained in a single HTML file. This example includes embedded CSS for styling and JavaScript for functionality. The app is a basic to-do list where users can add and remove tasks.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple To-Do List</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        #taskInput {
            width: 80%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 10px 0;
        }
        #addTaskButton {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        #taskList {
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
        }
        .task {
            background: #fff;
            margin: 5px 0;
            padding: 10px;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: center;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        .removeTaskButton {
            background: red;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 5px 10px;
            cursor: pointer;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>To-Do List</h1>
    <input type="text" id="taskInput" placeholder="Add a new task...">
    <button id="addTaskButton">Add Task</button>
    <ul id="taskList"></ul>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('addTaskButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const taskInput = document.getElementById('taskInput');
            const taskText = taskInput.value.trim();

            if (taskText) {
                const taskList = document.getElementById('taskList');
                const taskItem = document.createElement('li');
                taskItem.className = 'task';
                taskItem.innerHTML = `
                    ${taskText}
                    <button class="removeTaskButton">Remove</button>
                `;

                taskItem.querySelector('.removeTaskButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
                    taskList.removeChild(taskItem);
                });

                taskList.appendChild(taskItem);
                taskInput.value = '';
            } else {
                alert('Please enter a task.');
            }
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Paste it into a text editor and save it with a `.html` extension (e.g., `todo.html`).
3. Open the saved file in a web browser.

### Features:
- Users can add tasks to the list.
- Each task has a "Remove" button to delete it from the list.
- Basic input validation to ensure that empty tasks cannot be added.

Feel free to modify the styles and functionality as needed!
